  <table border='0' width='100%' cellspacing='0' cellpadding='5'>
    <tr>
      <td width='95%' align='left' valign='top' colspan=2 bgcolor='#000066' class='spti2'>ITEM COMMENTS</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td width='95%' align='left' valign='top' colspan=2 class='db'><span class='dbti'>SIGIL OF MINDSPARK</span><b>, By Beldhyr jogues</b> <small>(1/28/2001)</small><br><br>I am an impractical enchanter. Just thought I'd get that out of the way. You don't need to flame me for what I'm about to say.<P>
Did anyone ever stop to think that Enchanters are SUPPOSED to melee?  Ok, flame away.  But why not?  We aren't going to do enough damage to taunt and if we do, we can blur.  Or stun.  Or just take a few hits while the Tank continues to taunt.  Furthermore, our color spells are excellent caster interrupts...and we have to be in Melee range to use them anyway, so why not hit A?  If you remember to turn it OFF when you mez, you'll be fine.   Also, at lower levels we get player race illusions which allow us to slam.  This slam has the potential to interrupt casters, though I'd have to admit it's usually not worth the bother in lieu of our color stuns.  It does help our offense raise faster, however.<P> 
Which is another interesting point.  Our Defense rises at a rate of 3xlvl+15, while our Offense rises at a rate of 4xlvl.  Which means Offense quickly surpasses defense.  At 35th, that sets defense at 20 points lower than offense.  Why would verant give enchanters a higher offense than defense, if they were not meant to be in combat at all? I have been known to jump in and take hits to save my pet before when soloing. I told you, I'm an impractical enchanter.<P> 
Anyway, as I was saying, with the issue of Illusions.  At level 39 we get an illusion which raises our attack by 15, and at 44 we recieve Illusion:Werewolf which has the primary purpose of increasing our attack, that and making us non-kos in Splitpaw.
One more thing, as a rebuttal to the gentleman who said he would not haste himself unless it were mana-free: at level 29 we receive Augmentation, which I keep on myself at all times.  Impractical?  When you consider that it brings my Agility up to 110, which affects how much I dodge, it is thoroughly practical and an excellent use of 90 mana.<P>
All I'm saying is, I don't know everything about this game.  Here are some ideas, and they are only that -- ideas.  If you think they are stupid, fine, but explain yourself and present your arguments, please.<br><hr size='1'></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td width='95%' align='left' valign='top' colspan=2 class='db'><span class='dbti'>DAMN NICE ITEM !</span><b>, By The crakk man</b> <small>(1/28/2001)</small><br><br>It's so nice to see an item that enchanters are going to actually want. Awesome stats all the way around and it's a decent melee weap. I will surely need to quest this item in due time. This epic quest item makes up for our crappy uncontrollable pets we get! <br><hr size='1'></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td width='95%' align='left' valign='top' colspan=2 class='db'><span class='dbti'>THE BIG QUESTION.</span><b>, By Mystrall</b> <small>(1/28/2001)</small><br><br>I don't care to ever see spoilers on quests, and if I do, I scroll fast past it, but I don't mind if the begining is listed. There is my question, where does the Enchanter quest start?<br><hr size='1'></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td width='95%' align='left' valign='top' colspan=2 class='db'><span class='dbti'>JUST TO POINT OUT...</span><b>, By Cylos</b> <small>(1/28/2001)</small><br><br>Not that I'd ever suggest an enchanter get involved in ANY melee combat whatsoever, except maybe for fun on a stunned or running mob, or to trim those last 3 HPs off the mob that just won't die. That being said, this staff as a weapon is better than 11/24.   Why?  Because if you were using it in combat, you'd hasten yourself.   OK, yes, any enchanter CAN hasten themselves starting at lvl 12, but really, would they?  I wouldn't, unless it was A.) Mana free, and B.) in my spell line up already.   This staff satisfies both of those conditions, and with an instant cast/recast, I'd keep my self sped up and swinging in combat just to work my skill up beyond 12.<P>
So the point is, while the real stats are 11/24, the real practical stats are 11/9  (if I understand the effect of a 65% haste spell correctly).  This turns into a devastating weapon, even if your damage will still be only trivial compared to your tank.   Especially when you give your tank this buff.  Not that I'd ever encourage an Enchanter to melee. I thought it worth mention.   And yes, cheers and kudos for Verdant for a well balanced Partical Weapon.   I'll be getting one here in about a month - assuming I can level once a day.   No problem.   Did I say month?  I meant year…  

<br><hr size='1'></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td width='95%' align='left' valign='top' colspan=2 class='db'><span class='dbti'>LOOK</span><b>, By Braelyn</b> <small>(1/28/2001)</small><br><br>To the high elf enchanter who posted above. It's not all about the stats.  Sure you have 200 int, who doesn't? And sure your charisma is high, pretty impressive. But it's just being able to say &#34;I did the quest, I made it through, I did the hardest quest possible for my class, and I have this to prove it.&#34; I can understand you're a little cautious because of the risk but it's fun to take chances every now and then, not that you don't but this is more of a risk than usual.  Good luck to all the people doing/finding these quests and keep up the good work.
<br><hr size='1'></td>
    </tr>
